{
  "text": "Although it is impossible to assess the purity of microfilaments, the isolation method described here appears to be very specific. Neither class of microfilaments could be obtained if a specific monoclonal antibody was replaced by either a heatdenatured monoclonal antibody or another monoclonal antibody such as JLT12 against troponin T, which was known to be absent in microfilaments of nonmuscle cells. Furthermore, as described in previous reports [CITATION_1] , the isolation of Average values used here were obtained from four experiments by scanning fast-green-stained gels (see Materials and Methods). Molar ratios provided are given relative to the total amount of the tropomyosin (38,000, 36,500, and 32,800) . = aA, alpha-actinin ; TM, tropomyosin' (38,000, 36,500, and 32,800-mol-wt proteins) . Table I legend for symbols . ' Myosin ATPase activity was measured at 24\u00b0C and in the presence of 10 mM dithiothreitol. No ATPase activity can be detected in either one of the microfilament fractions alone or in ascites fluid alone . ' Parentheses indicate amounts of total proteins in each microfilament fraction . The total actin content in these fractions was estimated as about half of the total protein content, based on SDS polyacrylamide gel analysis of these fractions . 'Active actin content was expressed as the equivalent amount of muscle actin to show the same extent of activation on myosin ATPase activity.",
